To compute the current speed of an object, we need more information such as the distance traveled and the time taken to travel that distance. For simplicity, let's assume you have the distance in meters and the time in seconds. The formula for speed is:

\[ \text{Speed} = \frac{\text{Distance}}{\text{Time}} \]

Here's a simple C program that calculates the speed given the distance and time:

```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    // Declare variables
    float distance, time, speed;

    // Prompt user for input
    printf("Enter the distance traveled in meters: ");
    scanf("%f", &distance);

    printf("Enter the time taken in seconds: ");
    scanf("%f", &time);

    // Calculate speed
    if (time > 0) { // Avoid division by zero
        speed = distance / time;
    } else {
        printf("Error: Time cannot be zero.\n");
        return 1; // Exit with error code
    }

    // Print the result
    printf("The speed of the object is %.2f meters per second.\n", speed);

    return 0;
}
```

